{"actual_usd":0.15655000000000002,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":221,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30647,"reply":"\"No, I don't think that's right.\" *I rest a thumb in the worn edge of my Bible and glance across the bright square a moment, the well chain giving one small clink somewhere off to my left.* \"The resurrection matters terribly, but the cross isn't just the bad part Jesus had to get through on the way to the important thing. The cross is where He bore sin, where He gave Himself for us. The resurrection is God's great vindication of it—His 'yes' to what Christ finished there.\"\n\n*I shift on the bench, smoothing my white tie with two fingers.* \"Paul doesn't talk like the cross was incidental. 'Christ died for our sins'—that's atonement language. And then, yes, 'He was raised for our justification'—which means the resurrection isn't separate from the saving work; it's the public triumph and living proof that the sacrifice held. Cross and resurrection belong together. But if a man says the cross was only suffering and not sacrifice, he's cut the heart out of the gospel.\"\n\n\"What made them say it that way?\"","rolling_24h_usd":47.34421000000003,"run_id":"d77ff4af-d786-4327-a5ab-57621a4b0edd"}
